details.purpose: Record clinical examination findings on palpation of the fetus in utero, either from an abdominal or vaginal approach.
details.use:
Use to record examination findings on palpation of the fetus while in utero. This archetype can be used to record either abdominal or vaginal examination findings, including during labor.
This archetype has been designed to be nested inside the OBSERVATION.exam archetype or other relevant CLUSTER archetypes, for example providing specific detail about the fetus in CLUSTER.palpation_of_uterus.
Record the details of only one fetus using this archetype. Recording details about multiple fetuses will require the multiple separate instances of this archetype.

items.items: Examination of the fetus by palpation, using either an abdominal or vaginal approach.
Narrative description of findings on examination of the fetus.
Relationship of the longitudinal axis of the fetus to the long axis of the mother.
The fetal longitudinal axis is in alignment with the mother's longitudinal axis.
The fetal longitudinal axis is at right angles to the mother's longitudinal axis.
The fetal longitudinal axis is at an oblique angle to the mother's longitudinal axis. Sometimes also referred to as 'Unstable Lie'.
Identification of the part of the fetus lying in the lower part of the uterus.
The vertex is lying in the lower part of the uterus.
The breech is lying in the lower part of the uterus.
Relationship between the fetal denominator and the maternal pelvis.
For cephalic presentations, the denominator is the occiput; in breech presentations the denominator is the sacrum; and in face presentations the denominator is the mentum.
The fetal occiput is pointing towards the right. Also known as Right Occipito-Lateral (ROL).
The fetal occiput is pointing anteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal occiput is pointing posteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal occiput is pointing anteriorly, towards the pubic symphysis.
The fetal occiput is pointing posteriorly, towards the sacrum.
The fetal occiput is pointing towards the left. Also known as Left Occcipito-Lateral (LOL).
The fetal occiput is pointing anteriorly and towards the left.
The fetal occiput is pointing posteriorly and towards the left.
The fetal sacrum is pointing towards the right.
The fetal sacrum is pointing anteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal sacrum is pointing posteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal sacrum is pointing anteriorly, towards the pubic symphysis.
The fetal sacrum is pointing posteriorly, towards the sacrum.
The fetal sacrum is pointing towards the left.
The fetal sacrum is pointing anteriorly and towards the left.
The fetal sacrum is pointing posteriorly and towards the left.
The fetal chin is pointing towards the right.
The fetal chin is pointing anteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal chin is pointing posteriorly and towards the right.
The fetal chin is pointing anteriorly, towards the pubic symphysis.
The fetal chin is pointing posteriorly, towards the sacrum.
The fetal chin is pointing towards the left.
The fetal chin is pointing anteriorly and towards the left.
The fetal chin is pointing posteriorly and towards the left.
Description of the relationship of the fetal head and limbs to the body of the fetus on palpation.
The estimated proportion of the presenting part which is felt above the pelvic brim.
The head is not engaged in the pelvis.
About 20% of the head is inside the pelvis.
About 40% of the head is inside the pelvis.
About 60% of the head is inside the pelvis.
About 80% of the head is inside the pelvis.
The head is inside the pelvis.
Description of engagement of fetal head.
The presenting part is high and mobile.
The presenting part is at the pelvic brim.
The presenting part is engaged in the pelvis.
The relative size of the baby compared to the normal for the estimated gestation.
The size of the fetus appears smaller than expected for estimaged gestation.
The size of the fetus appears as expected for the estimated gestation.
The size of the fetus appears larger than expected for the estimated gestation.
The estimated weight of the fetus on palpation.
Identification of the presenting part of the fetus.
The vertex is the presenting part.
A fetal shoulder is the presenting part.
A fetal foot is the presenting part.
A fetal arm is the presenting part.
Record this separately as it is usually presenting with another body part eg breech or shoulder.
The face is the presenting part.
The brow is the presenting part.
Position of the presenting part relative to teh ischial spines.
Record -5 to -1cm for when the presenting part is above the ischial spines; record 0 at the ischial spines; and record 1 to 5 when the presenting part is below the ischial spines.
